<HEADLINE>
<P>
VENTURA COUNTY NEWSWATCH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Fred Alvarez 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 BERRY BONANZA: Finally, Super Strawberry can rest. With the California 
Strawberry Festival set to kick off Saturday in Oxnard (B1), the people picked 
to run around in giant red strawberry costumes and promote the event have 
completed their mission. . . . "The mascots do most of their duties before the 
event," explained festival spokeswoman Aileen Stein. . . . The four mascots, 
dubbed Super Strawberries, will receive passes to the festival and a free night 
at a hotel. Their costumes will be used by a church group to promote a 
strawberry-flavored drink at the festival. 
</P>
<P>
 ROOM FOR RENT? Ventura College unleashed 1,000 graduates into the real world 
Thursday (B1), but housing experts say many may have difficulty finding their 
first apartment (E3). . . . Some tips: Dress neatly, get it all in writing, and 
whatever you do, don't forget to pay the rent. . . . "It's very difficult to 
get your first apartment," says Mark Dolan, a Pasadena property manager. "Every 
landlord is looking for, No. 1, stability and ability to pay that rent." 
</P>
<P>
 PLAY BALL: David Rhoades has raised Moorpark High School's once-foundering 
baseball program to new heights (C10). . . . He has coached the Musketeers to a 
school record 19 wins, three consecutive league championships and six straight 
playoff appearances. . . . But he says he's most proud of his off-the-field 
influence. "More important than winning or losing out here is building some 
character in these kids and helping them to be good, class people," Rhoades 
said. 
</P>
<P>
 A DOG'S LIFE: Buddy was in love. So for a day, the loyal Labrador and 
top-notch arson investigator followed the call of the wild. . . . After 
wandering out of an open gate Monday, the 8-year-old canine was discovered a 
day later by Ventura County firefighters a few blocks away. And he wasn't 
alone. . . . "He likes to go on these romantic adventures," said fire 
investigator Bill Hager of the dog who uses his nose to help crack tough arson 
cases. "I think he was in love." 
</P>
