<P>
'CHUNNEL' HAS FIRST PAYING CUSTOMERS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Money finally flowed in, not out, as the $15-billion Channel Tunnel shuttled 
its first load of freight Thursday under the sea between Britain and France. 
</P>
<P>
 It still will be months before regular passengers can use the "Chunnel" and 
years before investors see profits, if ever. 
</P>
<P>
 But revenues started coming in Thursday when 14 trucks rolled onto the trains 
in Folkestone, bound for the Continent. German and French truckers boarded in 
Calais, France, to head for Britain. 
</P>
