<HEADLINE>
<P>
RUELAS TUNES UP AGAINST ALEXANDER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By TIM KAWAKAMI 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 With a title fight just over the horizon, Gabriel Ruelas has a 10-round 
tune-up tonight at the Olympic Auditorium against Paris Alexander, best known 
for being knocked out by Oscar De La Hoya in two rounds last year. 
</P>
<P>
 Ruelas (37-2, 20 knockouts), who was knocked down by Raul Hernandez in his 
last tune-up, is the No. 1 contender among World Boxing Council 
junior-lightweights and is due for a title fight against champion James Leija 
within 90 days. 
</P>
<P>
 Is the Ruelas camp worried that he might be looking past Alexander (16-8-3, 
three knockouts)? 
</P>
<P>
 "Every fight, you wonder if you're going to throw a wrench in the gears," said 
trainer Joe Goossen. "But we've got to fight guys like Paris Alexander to stay 
sharp. 
</P>
<P>
 "If you don't fight, you'll get rusty. If you do, you take your chances. But 
if you're going to go ahead and fight, make sure you're prepared." 
</P>
<P>
 Also on the card, which starts at 7:30, Jeremy Williams (15-1, 12 KOs) will 
fight Andrew Strokes (14-11-1, seven KOs) in a 10-round heavyweight bout. It is 
Williams' first fight since losing to Larry Donald last March. TIM KAWAKAMI 
</P>
</TEXT>
